Germany: a budgetary fetish that costs dearly
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is the subject of fierce attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of the independence of the central bank.
It was Germany that ensured this principle was incorporated into the criteria outlined by the Maastricht Treaty, which sets the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), granting independence to their central bank in order to join the euro zone implied a change in political regime.
Thus the independence of the Bank of France, during the ratification referendum of the Maastricht Treaty in 1992, was one of the strongest arguments of the campaign against joining the euro.
In today's Germany, on the other hand, it has become common practice, if one can put it that way, to put pressure on the central bank.
Since quelques mois, even the Minister of Finance, Wolfgang Schäuble, regularly comments on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Wolfgang Schäuble's interventions target the very heart of what constitutes the independence of the central bank.
If he does not seek to redefine the monetary policy objective (this 'price norm', in the old jargon of the Bundesbank), he nevertheless dispenses advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should handle them to achieve such a goal.
We have precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then Germany's Finance Minister, offered his good advice to the first ECB President, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's goal was to create, in the end, a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with typically Dutch laconism, replied that there was nothing incongruous about a politician expressing his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unusual). "After all – he added – it would be quite abnormal to take his suggestions into account."
Les critiques de Schaüble à l'égard de la BCE ne sont pas sans rappeler celles d'Oskar Lafontaine en 1998, qui avait également cherché à influencer la politique monétaire de la banque centrale.
Respect for monetary policy independence has long been a core element of Germany's Stabilitätkultur ("culture of stability").
The founding act of the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to the entreaties of Chancellor Konrad Adenauer, who wanted it to curb the rise in interest rates, in 1956.
At that time, France did not see things in the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was on the verge of creating the Fifth Republic, with a Bank of France that reported to the Minister of Finance.
It was a different time.
Following various crises that have shaken the EMU, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Has the old dogma become outdated?
The European continent remains highly vulnerable; the median inhabitant of the EMU has already lost ten years, and what is even more alarming, we are close to a critical situation.
The United States, for that matter, do better.
Despite a difficult-to-manage political deadlock, they were able to tackle the macro-economic problem (global demand weakness) they faced by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States have also better managed their banking problems, which were initially much more severe than in Europe.
There is, of course, a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
The more robust an economy is, the more profitable its banks are and the better they are able to fulfill their function: to finance the economy.
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a Minister of Finance than by the lack of support from the population.
And in fact, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, particularly in Germany, calling for it to be subjected to even greater pressures.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's autonomy lies in the unbearable burden that weighs on its shoulders.
The less the budget policy is solicited to stabilize production, the more central banks are effectively forced to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course, and allow the economy to stagnate, or worse).
The result of this political chain of events is a very clear regression towards nationalism, both from the right and the left, in all EU countries, including Germany.
The rising tide of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany sets the pace, with its obsession with the black zero, budgetary balance, against wind and tide.
In Germany, deficits are viewed unfavorably, not only from an arithmetic but also a moral standpoint, even though this defies sound economic sense and bears a resemblance to cronyism.
At the end of the 19th century, Germany's leading public finance specialists, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, forged a "golden rule" stipulating that current expenditures should be financed, on average, by current revenues.
Public expenditures and the resources they require are justified by their utility.
This is equivalent to saying that investments aimed at boosting productivity – capital expenditures – can be financed with debt, the servicing of which is ensured by the growth of income and the tax base associated with it.
This traditional approach has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment expenditures, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and in Austria).
It's crucial, because in Germany, about 50% of public sector investment expenditures are managed at this level (a proportion that has decreased, since the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with the support for the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (Mittelstand).
But compared to the beginning of the 1990s and at constant prices, investment expenditures have decreased by about 15%.
For more than a decade, they have been insufficient for maintaining the capital stock.
If that is not how one prepares the future, that is how one undermines productivity and prosperity.
The "black zero" goes against the desired goal.
Old infrastructures (certainly not as much as in the United States) have become a real problem for Germany.
In addition, the German leaders' budgetary frugality spills over beyond German borders and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which lacks an exchange rate to accommodate national particularities.
Of course, the European Monetary Union is imperfect.
But turning the only institution willing to "do what's needed" to bring the EMU back on track into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
That the member states use, where available, the budgetary space at their disposal to ease the pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, enjoys a certain degree of latitude in this regard.
